on":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Rea  .","English: topographic name for someone living at a place where rye (Old English <i>ryge</i>) was grown, or perhaps an occupational name for someone who grew or sold it.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads so named, most of them from Old Norse <i>rjóthr</i> ‘clearing in a forest’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ryer","meanings":["English (Sussex and Kent): probably from   Rye   (see   Rea  ) + the suffix <i>-er</i>, and is thus synonymous with Middle English <i>atte Rye</i>, denoting someone who lived by a river or an island. This type of formation is common in Sussex and Kent.","Americanized form of German   Reier   ‘heron’ or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rajar</b> or <b>Rajer</b> (see   Rayer  )."]},{"name":"Romney","meanings":["English: habitational name from Romney (Kent), from an uncertain first element (perhaps an Old English personal name <i>Rūmen</i>) + Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’. Compare   Rye   2."]},{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":7,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":20,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Edmund de Rye was born about 1308, in Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England as the son of Nicholas de Rye II and Margaret De Lincolnshire. He married Elizabeth Marmion about 1325. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died from 9 January 1332 to 8 January 1333, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1308–1332":"umbes 1308–9. jaanuar 1332 kuni 8. jaanuar 1333","1308–1332":"1308–9.jaanuar1332kuni8.jaanuar1333","1290–1371":"1290–1371","1315–1390":"1315–1390","1326–1370":"1326–1370","1335–1360":"1335–1360","–1307":"–1307","1263–Female":"1263–Surnud","1263":"1263","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","about 1308":"umbes 1308","1335":"1335","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1332":"9. jaanuar 1332 kuni 8. jaanuar 1333","about 1326":"umbes 1326","1308":"1308","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","of Beaurepaire, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Gosberton,Lincolnshire,England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England","Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1308–1332":"noin 1308–vuodesta 9. tammikuuta 1332 vuoteen 8. tammikuuta 1333","1308–1332":"1308–vuodesta9.tammikuuta1332vuoteen8.tammikuuta1333","1290–1371":"1290–1371","1315–1390":"1315–1390","1326–1370":"1326–1370","1335–1360":"1335–1360","–1307":"–1307","1263–Female":"1263–Kuollut","1263":"1263","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","about 1308":"noin 1308","1335":"1335","about 1325":"noin 1325","1332":"vuodesta 9. tammikuuta 1332 vuoteen 8. tammikuuta 1333","about 1326":"noin 1326","1308":"1308","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","of Beaurepaire, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Gosberton,Lincolnshire,England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, Engla